This is a slightly modified version of the original Filament Feeder and Cap for kameya's Filament Storage Box.

Also note that, in keeping with the original feeder assembly design by kameya, a small amount of space has been preserved within the cap to allow for the Hole Seal Pads.

Last but not least, much thanks to kameya for designing this Filament Storage Box. We've been using ours for almost 6 months, often in heavy production intervals, and it's held up 100% solid.

This is Day 9 of my collection of printable equations. To see the whole collection, go to: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:227210 For today's equation, we have the final in the series of equations of the form |x^b + y^c| = a (See days 2, 6, 7, and 8). Previously, we saw that as b and c went from <1, to 1, to >1, to 2, the quadrants of the shape went from bending inward, to straight, to bowing out, to a circle. As b,c --> infinity, the quadrants continue to extend out until they form a square. Today's equation: x^20 + y^20 = a, is a close approximation of that, though you can still see some rounding at the corners. You can see the progression in the posted photo. Details:
  • units are in mm
  • a = 50^20 (to give a length and height of 100)
  • Range(x) = -50 to 50
  • stl resized to make x axis = 100 mm
    • As always, I'm going to continue to post one equation per day until get bored or people lose interest. If there's a particular equation you'd like to see, leave a comment and I'll give it a shot.

Our collection of 3D-printable gear mechanisms would be incomplete without the model of a screw gear drive. Screw gears are regular helical gears mounted on non-parallel, non-intersecting shafts. They are also known as crossed helical gears.

The shape of this screw gear drive was inspired by the DNA molecule. In this particular model, there are three gears mounted at 45° to each other, but the shaft angle can be any number between 0 and 90°.

title: 1991 Honda CRX Tail Light Trim Panels

description.text:
These are a set of replacement panels for the stock interior panels that cover the tail light bulbs.
The STLs are for both sides, the source file is for the left panel only - just mirror it for the right side.

Print face down with no raft or support. If you use blue painter's tape as the surface, you get the added bonus of a nearly identical texture as the original part.
After printing, heat the edge of the part gently with a hairdryer or heatgun to soften it, and give it a gentle bend like the original. You shouldn't have to heat the thin panel, just the thick edges.
I highly suggest using ABS instead of PLA. I tried it in PLA and the heat from the bulbs has warped the panels.

  • use them as a stopper to get perfect 90° angles
  • use them as risers (bench cookies) for sinding/grinding by printing the top layers using filaflex
  • print longer benches and add a screw to make a guiding rail's support

I found several 3d printed puzzle map on the site but none for Canada so I decided to make my own. Using Fusion 360, I imported an svg file of a map i previously found on the internet. I then extruded all the different provinces to make the pieces. To account for the northern islands without over complicating the puzzle made a piece representing the ocean unto which all of the islands can be fitted in their correct locations. Very well suited for basic geography teaching in all schools or at home, as the students get a physical feel of the provinces and their respective sizes.

The process I used to design the map could be adapted to create puzzle maps of pretty much any country or region provided you have a 2d black and white map of it.

Basically I modified the original battery-tray and designed a mount to get the yaw-motor fixed in front and up a bit. Then I made the arm from the yaw- to the roll-motor.
I took the remaining parts from my 2-axis gimbal, wich in turn is a remix of MikeyB´s gimbal.

The first version showed extreme shaking and trembling. Members of the rcgroup helped me to find out, that the tray with the gimbal in front is a cantilever and that the vibrations led to a kind of mechanical resonance which caused the shaking. The battery-tray and the top-arm where not stiff enough.

So I made the tray-front thicker, the motor-mount shorter and the arm stiffer - this helped. Have a look at the video. The short footage was not stabilized afterwards.

title: Poor Man's 4th Axis cnc
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
In order to give tires of my model cars a final touch I was thinking of using a 4th axis for rotary engraving. For the vague idea, the intense investment and due to harsh software requirement it did not get a professional 4th axis set. It came in handy that I had a stepper motor (I changed from my y-axis) and a small chuck laying around. So I designed the pm4a.

This build was done on a desktop cnc-machine by Stepcraft from 6.5 mm birch plywood for the body and some 5 mm Pertinax for the gears using a 1.2 mm spiral toothed flute. Furthermore I used

  • 2 Ballbearings Type 6000ZZ (10 x 26 x 8 mm)
  • 1 Ballbearing Type 608ZZ (8 x 22 x 7 mm)
  • small chuck (10 mm 3/8'' x 24 UNF) with SDS-Plus-adapter
  • NEMA17 stepper
  • a sharpened M8 machine screw and a selflocking nut (for the tailstock)
  • some M3 machine screws

The two gears have an pretty uncommon cycloidal (round) teeth, which helped me to create smaller teeth, because they don't have any corners. Otherwise the teeth size would have been limited by the diameter of my milling bit.

The motor is driven by plugging it into the X-axis stepper driver. This way the machine won't move sideways, but instead the workpiece does. The distance of travel for one revolution is calculated depending of the diameter of the workpiece dived by the gear reduction of 6 : 1. For example my tires have 40 mm diameter. So the circumference is 40 mm x π (3.1415) = 125.66 mm / 6 = 20.94 mm. I entered this value in the controller settings.

When using the pm4a it'd be a good idea to use some kind of cover to prevent dust from getting into the gearing.

Visit https://www.zenziwerken.de/en/ for more interesting designs.
The prototype did use a different (even smaler chuck) which had a attached hex bolt. It proved the concept, but was to shaky to be of good use. This shows the operation of the prototype.

title: Anet A6 Bed Y-axis Cable Chain (front mount)

description.text: This project solved two issues for me. I have my A6 mounted in a Lack type enclosure so I wanted to move the wires from the rear of the bed to the front since a cable chain wouldn't have room at the back of the printer (requires rotating the bed on the "H" frame 180 degrees). I also needed to directly solder the bed connection to remedy the common problem of the Anet bed connector working loose. This cable chain would probably work with the stock connector but is much cleaner if you solder the wires at a 90 degree angle to the bed. I remixed the bed side mount from DarthVader911 http://thingiverse.com/thing:2215560, adding support to one of the uprights where the chain connects (my first one broke because the first links I printed were too tight). His used a store bought cable chain, so I then remixed the chain links from scorpianuk http://thingiverse.com/thing:2067601 to make them fit the mount. I also reduced the width of the connectors on the male side so that they could be more easily assembled and would move freely. The internal space for the wires to pass thru is 10mmx10mm. The mount requires drilling the "H" frame and using bolts to secure it. I used M3x12 screws and nuts but you could also drill and tap if you wanted. The back of the cable chain is secured to the table, but there is a frame screw close by on the A6 that could be made to work with a remix of the end piece (Male_End_mod.stl).

title: GeeeTech i3 Pro B Air Duct

description.text:
I've designed this air duct for a 50mm radial fan on my GEEETech I3 Pro B after using XDr4g0nX's fan shroud for quite a while (thanks for the design!).

However, I think my approach has several advantages:

  • The base and the throat are much more slender. So it doesn't conceal so much of your prints and it does not hit the glass clamps.
  • Its height is adjustable in the range of 3.5 mm which may help to avoid some obstacles.
  • The ring has a lot more holes which are directed downwards instead of rather inwards. Thus it cools your printed part instead of the nozzle. The airflow is significantly stronger.

I printed it in PETG. The included supports can easily be removed.

Now there is a second version that adds a mount for the BLTouch. However, I didn't test this one. It would be nice, if someone could post, if it fits or not.

June 3 2017: Update of the BLTouch version

  • I moved the BLTouch mount 3mm to the outside as the screws for attaching the duct and the BLTouch came really close.
  • I closed the 0.1mm gap between the BLTouch mount and the support structure as this caused printing in air.

Functional "sweet potato" style ocarina. English 5-hole fingering. Plays A4 - B5 -- might be some variation/error depending on your printer. Was surprised not to see any examples of working printable traditional-form ocarinas up here, so I made this up. Let me know what you think, or recommend any changes. If anyone's interested, I'll make some alternate versions (fingering patterns, shapes, keys). edit-- whoa, wasn't expecting this much attention. If you like this thing, tips are appreciated. btc: 13aNJBe4SAKhaALa9cnszfPWhSxvhz95n6

The ocarina is split into two halves for reliable printing without support material. Don't rescale it (original size should be ~4.25" long) or it won't play as expected. Print the halves with the flat side down. Use the thinnest layer height you can manage to help prevent problems with the voicing (I used .1mm / MakerWare 'High' preset).  
After printing, glue the halves together. Make sure there are no air leaks along the edges.  
If you have a printer with dissolvable support material, you should be able to recombine the halves and print it as a single piece, but make sure the airway doesn't get clogged with support.

description.text:
These castors are self-steering, providing smooth roll in any direction, and use common 608 skateboard bearings for radial and axial load.

For 1 full castor you need:

  • 1x 3d printed wheel
  • 1x 3d printed castor body
  • 2x 3d printed bearing flanges.
  • 4x 608 series (skateboard) bearings.
  • 2x washers either side of the wheel bearings (2mm of thickness either side).
  • 1x m8 axle bolt/rod (approx 60mm) for the wheel.
  • 1x m8 threaded rod for the swivel axis, length to suit your application. Best to use high tensile or stainless rod for strength.
  • 8x wood screws to attach the bearing blocks to your structure. I use phosphated drywall screws because they have a real grippy texture and sharp thread.
  • several M8 nuts to screw it all together, depending on whether you use bolts or threaded rod.

Recommended to print in ABS or something durable and strong - the wheels will suffer from wear the most.

The tolerances are tuned to my printer - so they might be a little loose if your printer is calibrated to be 100% dimensionally accurate.
For example - the bearing bores are 22.2mm which is about 0.9% oversize. I found on my printer after ABS shrinkage, the bearings press in under light finger pressure.
Please print a sample wheel/flange first!
I apologize to anyone who printed V 1 as the bearing size was wrong, MY BAD.

For Trex 450 PRO DFC.

Print feet flat on the bed for strength.
Print legs on the side for strength.

Reuse the original buttonhead screws for the fuselage.

Nyloc - 3mm DIN 985

Enjoy.

title: Astroprint Set for Monoprice Maker Select Plus

description.text:
Add a Raspberry Pi 2 or 3 (plus power supply and SD card) and a Microsoft LifeCam 3000 to create an entire Astroprint (or Octoprint) setup with a bed mounted camera for your Monoprice Maker Select Plus printer.

This is a remix and modification of several other things as noted in the sidebar. I modified the sleeve adding larger openings to make connecting power easier and scaled up the entire object to make inserting and removing the whole Raspberry Pi easier. I combined the two camera arms into one and did not modify the bed mount.

Printing and Usage: Print the bed mount with supports and a raft in ABS or PETG; others can be printed without supports or rafts in PLA. The hole in the bed mount is for an M3 screw and nut to clamp the mount to the bed; you can use one of the short screws you removed from the printer frame to mount the sleeve. The camera mount and bed mount are bolted together using a longer M3 screw and nut. The sleeve is mounted by replacing the short M3's in the vertical upright with longer versions; there are no nuts as the screws attach directly to the printer frame. The bed mount and camera mount can be used together on other printers as well. I mounted to the back of this printer; have also designed a shorter mount to reduce required desk depth.

Pi3: https://www.amazon.com/Raspberry-Model-A1-2GHz-64-bit-quad-core/dp/B01CD5VC92

Microsoft LifeCam 3000: https://www.amazon.com/Microsoft-T3H-00011-LifeCam-HD-3000/dp/B005BZNEKM

Octoprint: http://octoprint.org/

Happy printing and filming!

After installing a e3d v6 head in my MP Mini, I noticed the amount of space to let the air crossing the heatsink out the back was minimal. I could feel backwash from the fan so air was definitely not flowing unobstructed.

This is a remix of a 40mm fan duct, but I cannot find the original. I have printed many ducts but none fit the e3d v6 clone as well as this duct. The design is excellent and prints perfectly with no supports or anything.

So to allow more air to flow over the heatsink and out the sides, I created 2 remixes with exhaust ports on the sides. One with 3mm circles, one with a 3x15mm rectangle hole. This allows you to use the popular e3d mounts for the MP mini while allowing for plenty of air to cross the heatsink.

I printed in PLA with 100% infill and have had no problems with heat up to 220c. I use a 12v 40x30mm fan running on 5v. Runs very quiet and cool.

The notch cut out may be a little bit of a tight fit so it holds the gimbal guard in place. If you need to widen it, you can easily cut a little away with a hobby knife, or a small file.

Update - there are two styles of the gimbal guard protector. The original one (V3) allows the sticks to protrude slightly (about 5mm) above the guard. After getting some feedback on the design, I made another version (v3-high) that should keep the sticks completely covered. This will add extra protection so the sticks can't be pushed in easily. Disclaimer: I haven't printed this new version yet, but all I did was increase the height, so it should be fine. If you try it, please post a "make" here. The "high" version will only take an additional 15 minutes or so to print according to my slicer.

This is my custom 3D printer build. It has a build plate of 17" x 17" (About 430 mm squared) and uses a bowden extruder. I'm not sure what the max Z height will be yet. The frame is constructed of 2020 V-slot extrusion and it uses openbuilds wheels for y axis travel. The bed is attached to the Z axis, and the Y axis moves along the top of the printer carrying the X axis. This is most definitely a work in progress as I still need to design the X carriage. All of the joints are printed and you can find my onshape document ,where the parts are, and the assembly is shown here: https://cad.onshape.com/documents/8b00d2851b45bbaf94ac8704/w/239278736d9a6c2c57f70a18/e/49ebc18c666322a2cea93dfd

title: Tronxy X3 Y Vertical Stepper Mount & Belt Holders

description.text:
Y axis stepper motor mount to turn the stepper vertical. I converted the bed to linear rails and wanted to eliminate all the original Y axis hardware.

Stepper Motor Mount:
Printed with supports for the mounting tabs
.2mm layer height, 20% infill

Belt Holders do not require support. They need to be mounted on the left side of the bed to keep Y direction correct. 2 holes for each mount need to be drilled into the acrylic plate. Uses the 3x20mm screws included with the printer. Also you'll need about 95cm of belt. If you've trimmed your original belt, it probably won't be long enough.

Will require a new Y stop mount, which can be found here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2345504

I used Kryptonit3's belt tensioner: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2221061
And kencam's rod holders: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2185364

I've included Fusion360 archive files, if anyone wants to modify the original files.
